    <p> After I had released the motorhome again, Christchurch was now in front of me for 3 days. First I decided to go towards the city center and to see what is left of the city, after 4 large and over 10,800 small earthquakes in the past 2 years. </p>
    <p> In the bus I read what of a red zone in the city center on a advertising sign. With a little googling, I found out that most of the city center is still completely closed. When I arrived there I saw what earthquakes could do with my own eyes for the first time. The entire business center of the city is gone or is being demolished. A road card was then drawn on the fence, which is blocked. Pretty much the entire city center. As far as I could see, there were buildings that were partially destroyed and were only waiting for their demolition. The cathedral was still in front of it, but the bell tower had collapsed and already removed. </p>
    <p> Since the entire shopping mile was also affected, the residents have come up with a really good temporary solution. A temporary shopping street was simply built from trucks containers on an open area. </p>
